Plant Growth Project¶

Introduction¶

With this data set I am trying to find the most important set of variables to controll for consistent plant growth. I would assume that it would include fertilizer and soil type. I will read in the data, assess normality, create visuals of the data to better assess it, and run many correlation matrices to narrow down variables of importance.

Here is the link to the data set!

Describing The Data Set¶

Soil_Type: The type or composition of soil in which the plants are grown.

Sunlight_Hours: The duration or intensity of sunlight exposure received by the plants.

Water_Frequency: How often the plants are watered, indicating the watering schedule.

Fertilizer_Type: The type of fertilizer used for nourishing the plants.

Temperature: The ambient temperature conditions under which the plants are grown.

Humidity: The level of moisture or humidity in the environment surrounding the plants.

Growth_Milestone: Descriptions or markers indicating stages or significant events in the growth process of the plants.

It doesn’t really matter what soil type you have the plant in; they all have about a 50% success rate. It is obvious that there are more important factors in play than soil type. It could be that different humidity levels work better with different soils. Also, it would depend on the climate, drainage level, heat, and plant type. There are many factors that go into growing a plant. I can attempt to find the perfect combination for this specific type of plant."

This violin plot show us that each soil type does have a preffered humidity type. Loam soil reacts best to humidity being around 55%. Sandy soil does best around 55%, and clay does best at a higher humidity, closer to 60-65%.

Further extrapolating on humidity and soil type I wanted to add the fertilizer variable to the analysis. This is showing that certain Fertilizer types work best with different soil types, and we can still see groupings at what seem to be the best humidity levels.

Best soils and humidity levels for each fertilizer type¶

Chemical Fertilizer¶

Clay soil at 55-60% humidity was the most successful

Organic Fertilizer¶

Sandy soil had the least number of failures using organic fertilizer, this would be my recommendation, when kept below 70% humidity especially there were very few failed plants. Loam soil type was also very successful at a humidity level from 45-55%.

No Fertilizer¶

Loam was the soil type which has the most success for this fertilizer type, however, generally using no fertilizer meant the plants had a bad chance at reaching their growth milestone. Notably clay soil type was the worst, which a large grouping of failed plants at 70% humidity.

**Mapping variables

*Key

Water_Frequency -daily = 1 -weekly = 2 -bi-weekly = 3

Soil_Type -loam = 1 -sandy = 2 -clay = 3

Fertilizer_Type -none = 0 -organic = 1 -chemical = 2

I need variables to be numerical instead of strings to make it easier to do analysis with, by mapping these strings to 1s, 2s, and 3s I will be able to run correlation tests to see which variables I should be loooking at.

In [63]:
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Define pairs of variables to create heatmaps
pairs_of_vars = [
    # Soil_Type and Temperature_Binned as rows
    (['Soil_Type', 'Temperature_Binned'], ['Humidity_Binned', 'Water_Frequency']),
    (['Soil_Type', 'Temperature_Binned'], ['Fertilizer_Type', 'Sunlight_Hours_Binned']),
    
    # Soil_Type and Temperature_Binned as columns
    (['Humidity_Binned', 'Water_Frequency'], ['Soil_Type', 'Temperature_Binned']),
    (['Fertilizer_Type', 'Sunlight_Hours_Binned'], ['Soil_Type', 'Temperature_Binned']),
    
    # Soil_Type and Temperature_Binned mixed with other pairs
    (['Soil_Type', 'Temperature_Binned'], ['Humidity_Binned', 'Fertilizer_Type']),
    (['Soil_Type', 'Temperature_Binned'], ['Sunlight_Hours_Binned', 'Water_Frequency'])
]

# Create subplots
n_vars = len(pairs_of_vars)
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=n_vars, ncols=1, figsize=(25, 10 * n_vars))
fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.4)

# Generate heatmaps for each pair of variable combinations
for ax, (index_vars, column_vars) in zip(axes, pairs_of_vars):
    heatmap_data = pd.pivot_table(
        non_zero_combinations,
        values='Count',
        index=index_vars,
        columns=column_vars,
        aggfunc='sum'
    ).fillna(0)
    
    sns.heatmap(heatmap_data, cmap='YlGnBu', annot=True, fmt='g', ax=ax)
    ax.set_title(f'Heatmap: {", ".join(index_vars)} vs {", ".join(column_vars)}')
    ax.set_xlabel(', '.join(column_vars))
    ax.set_ylabel(', '.join(index_vars))

plt.show()

Across all of these heat maps it is clear that Sandy soil with high heat, medium humidity, daily watering, organic fertilizer, and medium to high sunlight hours is the beat combination for consistently reaching the growth milestone!

The impacts of this project are small. Unfortunately, the owner of this dataset did not include the plant type; some plants may require different growing conditions, so this is not a guide for every plant. A negative outcome could be someone with a plant that needs low heat and low light exposure trying to follow these guidelines and inadvertently killing their plant! I would feel terrible to find out this research did not work for them and they had a negative experience with growing anything. Knowing the plant type would make this dataset and research very useful for someone wanting to bulk-produce, set up a greenhouse environment, or increase plant growth speeds and overall health/happiness.
